uesday night.  by 9pm, though, the place was full.  the food is actually better than some of the reviews i read.  but you won\\\'t get out cheap, as some of the (most-likely) self-posted reviews on Yelp will tell you.  the food selection is diverse, tasty and comes out quickly.  the cocktail menu has some good picks also.  some of the interior design falls short of well-done, but overall it\\\'s a comfortable enough place to dine.  where it excels is service.  the staff is knowledgeable and helpful and on top of it.  i will continue to go back until the lines get out of control.  maybe when they extend the hours it will make a good lunch/afternoon spot.  UPDATE: went back a second time and was not as thrilled, felt like there was some stress building up amongst the staff.  we had subpar service and the food didn\\\'t seem as fresh.  maybe it was just the vibe..  interesting, though, that the place was half empty at 9pm on a saturday.','2009-03-25 16:02:18',2,64),(306,'This little neighborhood gem has got great subs - make your own or pick one of the house specialties. ','2009-03-06 16:05:39',7,64),(308,'Reliably good comfort food.','2009-03-06 16:12:54',7,64),(317,'must go back here!','2009-03-07 02:23:02',2,64),(322,'This comfortable downtown hotel is a nice place to stay but not over the top.  the rooms are relatively small, yet well-appointed -- they do provide robes, natch.  the usual touches of newly updated hotels are all there: the iPod radio, the flat panel TV.  we were upgraded just for being good looking.  and the folks at the desk were also attractive and attentive.  with the economic downturn, now is the time to blow your hard-earned money on some of the specials you can find.  the Staycation (a term which jumped the shark out the gate) is embraced: inexpensive rooms, free valet parking.  it\'s hard to pass up.  the hotel bar is, well, not really a hotel bar.  but that can be forgiven.  a late dinner menu and 24-hour room service is a plus.  ','2009-03-09 10:49:43',2,64),(324,'This romantic little italian eatery is hidden behind a non-descript doorway at the base of some of the Pearl\'s older lofts.  inside is cozy with seating downstairs and up in a loft.  we only discovered it during a pearl walkabout and stopped in for a drink.  the staff was friendly enough and the atmostphere felt convivial.  the food looked good and the clientelle had a distinction: though casual, they seemed to understand they held a secret knowledge that many did not.  i look forward to trying out the food first hand.  reviews online are mixed.  could be a roll of the dice on service.  play along and i bet you\'ll be rewarded.','2009-03-12 14:28:27',2,64),(327,'this trendy spot at the end of restaurant row set some high expectations.  when the whole wood-fire oven/artisan pizza thing finally reached portland a few years agao -- a few years behind the curve -- foodies went apeshit.  this restaurant\'s business hasn\'t slowed much since they opened.  but i felt like St. Paddy\'s day was the day to go and turned out to be right.  a table was open upon arrival.  waitstaff was friendly and attentive.  they\'ve only got a beer and wine license, and the beer selection leaves one wanting.  the menu is basic: a few salads and pizzas.  the cesar was decent, nothing special.  so i was all the more excited to try what must be some really special pizza!  bzzzzzz!  the pizza over at apizza scholls is better, and that\'s not saying much!  artisan pizza can be so good -- see &lt;a href=&quot;http://skipspicks.net/pizetta/id/251/z/15/&quot;&gt;Pizzeta&lt;/a&gt; in San Francisco -- but so far Portland has missed the mark.  this pizza is tasty, don\'t get me wrong, but it just isn\'t on par with great artisan pizza.','2009-03-18 13:07:04',2,64),(329,'rumor has it the launch was last night (March 25).  not a lot of information but the space alone is supposed to be worth checking out.  over the top decor, feels like you beemed onto buck roger\\\'s starship.  th