s is a handy little place to try if in the area.','2009-06-16 13:21:34',2,64),(387,'the classic madonna inn, with its themed rooms, is showing some age, but gracefully.  it\\\'s a must-stop destination for a drink or some food.  with outrageous decorations that change with the seasons and live music for dancing many nights a week.  this is an old-timer\\\'s favorite and the drinks show it.  get a shrimp cocktail!','2009-06-16 13:23:57',2,64),(389,'A great place to stop after a long day on the 5. They\'re a few littered up and down the 5, so if you see one andyou need some proper grub stop and check it out. Also, I\'m really wanting to try the original in Mt. Shasta. Oh and the decor is great - full on bear action in the best way. They even have cubbie socks!','2009-06-17 11:39:21',7,64),(395,'Finally dropped in on one of the newer (though not really new anymore) carts at the SW 5th and Stark cart pod.  when it first opened i got excited that there would be something to cure my cajun fix close by work, but then a coworker mumbled about the high price and small portions before i could stop by.  daily i would think to go and decide on somewhere else due to this coworker\\\'s report.  i\\\'m glad i finally went: friendly service, tasty food.  the portions must have gotten bigger because the serving of Jambalaya i had was plenty.  by the end, it was slightly dry, but that\\\'s my only complaint.  good spices, good mix of ingredients.  the wooden \\&quot;swamp shack\\&quot; decor built around the cart is classic, with the straight from new orleans hanging moss.  there\\\'s even a place to sit and eat.  definitely worth a try.','2009-07-13 14:31:22',2,64),(396,'The Corbett Fish House has been a great neighborhood place for fish going on a while so i was happy to see them expand over to Hawthorne; closer to me!  The place is clean, friendly, not usually too crowded.  What makes it a standout is how non-greasy everything is.  You sort of think of grease when you think fish and chips.  Not so here.  They flash-fry the fish (bite-sized chunks) in a rice-based oil i believe.  Whatever, it works.  The fries (chips) are some of the best around, but you can get your fish served on a sandwich or in tacos.  They\\\'ve got your cod and halibut jokes covered.  Lots of gluten-free action on the menu, too, if that\\\'s your thing.  Don\\\'t forget to try the sopa de pescado: spicy goodness.  What really keeps me coming back is the great service.  ','2009-07-15 14:55:02',2,64),(397,'great little bar that i\\\'m always forgetting about.  has a patio, nice servers with good cocktail knowledge','2009-07-20 14:29:28',2,64),(398,'Decent bar with outdoor area up on alberta','2009-07-20 14:30:20',2,64),(399,'Nice outdoor area in this sometimes over-capacitated bar','2009-07-20 14:31:30',2,64),(401,'Portland institution over by the burnside skatepark industrial area.  nice little back patio also.  food\\\'s above average for pub grub.','2009-07-20 14:36:34',2,64),(404,'Beaker and Flask opened quietly about a month ago and I finally got a chance to visit last night.  I still need to stop in a few times, try the dinner, but first impressions were good.  Situated in a nice building, booths line the outer walls.  Huge windows on the round dining room area.  There\\\'s a curving bar with nice glass tiles below.  The shelves behind the bar hold nicknacks from the cocktail\\\'s heyday.  This is a place that takes its drinks seriously, it\\\'s nice that the cocktail thing is sort of still on an upswing in portland.  The drink menu has some interesting concoctions, shying away from vodka as is the new vogue -- one of which i approve!  A good happy hour also includes some interesting takes on everyday items.  It\\\'s on the pricey side -- 8 to 9 bucks a drink versus Victory\\\'s 6.50 -- but the pours are good.  And at happy hour many of them go down to 5 bucks!  Staff is friendly and attentive; a skilled, professional bartender would be icing on the cake.  Highly recommended.','2009-07-29 16:44:22',2,64),(405,'this place has a quiet but huge following.  well, probably not quiet, i\\\'m just not following the same media channels as these kids.  it was like hipster pizza for young foodies.  i\\\'m getting ahead of my story and don\\\'t read anything negative into that last comment.\r\n\r\na -- god i hate the word foodie, don\\\'t you? -- a \\&quot;foodie\\&quot; friend of mine sent me a link to some LA food blog and asked if i\\\'d been to the places it talked about.  i\\\'d never heard of Dove Vivi.  i take that back.  a friend a while back said i should give it a try but it was off my radar.  anyway, the blog mentioned Dove and there was a picture of a wedge of iceberg lettuce with dressing.  so simple and elegant and trashy in one package, and it looked GOOD.  so we went.\r\n\r\nthe pizza is sort of this deep dish thing with a cornmeal crust.  comes in 1 size, six slices, and can feed 2 or 3 folks.  we got the coppa: mozzarella, provolone, italian ham, green olives.  great mix, well cooked, tasty.  i have to admit the cornmeal crust makes for a kind of dry angle, that just required a little more malty lubrication.  plus, that iceberg wedge, with its bluecheese goodness, had prepared me.\r\n\r\nwe got there a little after 6 and got a table right away and i was thinking, \\&quot;maybe this place *isn\\\'t* too hip yet.\\&quot;  well, with my back to the room and good company across the table, i didn\\\'t notice until we left that the place had filled out and there were throngs of people waiting to be seated.  the strange thing was how young the crowd was, not your usual over-30 food crowd.  i guess it\\\'s only natural for pizza to inspire young foodies.  it made me appreciate the friendly service that much more.','2009-08-11 10:59:49',2,64),(407,'I love this place. It\'s super punk rock, and yes, there can be a line for a beer. But rumor has it they\'re bringing in more workers who can pour more than a single beer at a time.  