nder a heat lamp and clientelle that is LEGIT.  check it.','2008-10-30 10:22:23',2,63),(209,'people won\'t soon forget the restaurant that made this locations name any time soon -- Taqueria Neuve.  needless to say, Tapalaya has big shoes to fill right off the bat.  only open two days, we decided to take our chances even though there was only one other table of diners in the space.  the new restaurant hasn\'t changed much of the decor, the tiled bar remains untouched, along with most of the room.  our waiter was a little overbearing yet very accomodating.  the combination of small plates with cajun food (tapas + jambalaya = tapalaya) isn\'t a bad concept though feels forced here with the terrible name lingering in the back of your mind.  all of our choices from the menu were very good, but something is definitely missing.  it might be the lack of bonhomie one might expect from a cajun restaurant, or the lack of the requisite cocktail menu.  time will tell.  i wish they\'d given the place a little more flavor of its own.  i just hope they can pull it together and create a great go-to in this downturned economy.  i wish them well and will go back again.','2008-11-07 00:23:27',2,63),(217,'funky little bar tucked into a quaint little corner of SoHo.  good atmosphere, strong drinks, eclectic clientelle.','2008-12-03 11:07:35',2,63),(218,'swank bar with good drinks if you\'re in the neighborhood','2008-12-03 11:09:56',2,63),(219,'Anthony Bourdaine\'s place.  french meets steak.  check out the extra strange advertising posters on the walls.  nice bar.  haven\'t eaten here, just had a drink from the hip, douchey bartender.','2008-12-03 11:12:43',2,63),(223,'great little irish bar where regulars and stragglers combine with an ambience of old school.','2008-12-04 09:07:01',2,63),(233,'24 hour diner.  don\'t remember anything about it except the guys were nice.','2008-12-08 14:20:03',2,63),(236,'always forget about this place, but it\'s clean and welcoming and always fun to burn some meat','2008-12-24 23:53:01',2,63),(244,'the bar at the recently remodeled -- and not to much fanfare i must add -- Hotel 50.  the waitress we had seemed slightly retarded, giving us attitude for calling her on giving us attitude.  they have a precious idea: match a specialty drink with an appetizer.  but what if i just want my drink?  they don\'t seem like the place that can be flexible.  it\'s not wonder the place was dead on a friday, they don\'t get it.  let\'s hope they run through this shitnest of a staff and load up with some people that know how to run a good bar.','2009-01-27 16:45:05',2,63),(325,'this spot kind of opened quietly a couple years back when the neighborhood (The Taint: between the couch and the ash!) was rebuilding.  overnight a following of sad-looking hipsters postured themselves at the bar like so many barnacles.  pshaw!  for a while i think this bar could have competed for the city\'s smokiest.  but lately for some reason it\'s back in the rotation.  and i\'ll tell you why: $1 tecates at happy hour.  that\'s why.  so go suffer a few overcool folk and thank the nice bartender for appreciating the business.','2009-03-16 17:16:35',2,63),(326,'this place opened quietly a few weeks ago and we drove past last night and noticed it for the first time.  finally someone has done away with the kitschy bahama motif and gone with a more straightforward approach.  the location has been cursed, and even with the change i\'m not sure how this place is going to do.  there\'s a slight irish feel to the place and yet it was basically empty on St. Patrick\'s day.  staff was extremely friendly and the bartender knowledgeable.  haven\'t tried the food yet, but it look like basic faire.  it would be nice to see a place like this come into its own and become part of the neighborhood, a place to go when the side street and belmont\'s make you nauseous.  tough road ahead, i wish them luck.','2009-03-18 12:52:23',2,63),(343,'This unassuming brewery, tucked int