ss near our hotel.  fish was fresh, place was full of people that looked to be in the know.  friendly service, decent prices.  i\\\'d go back.','2009-11-23 22:32:27',2,64),(438,'This informal spot has been running for years.  they serve high quality food from burgers, pastas, and on up to entrees.  not cheap, but you\\\'ll get good service and have an experience.  it\\\'s a classic SF spot','2009-11-30 16:16:33',2,65),(439,'This is one of the many diners strewn around union square area that are open late.  that might be the only reason to try them out.  that\\\'s why i was here.  Daily Grill was closed.  I should have tried one of the dirtier, more authentic looking spots but wasn\\\'t in the mood.  food here wasn\\\'t anything horrible, but the staff was all hanging out in a booth drinking.  the one gal who did help me was nice enough.  everyone here seemed to be russian.','2009-11-30 16:26:26',2,63),(440,'the restaurant in the Hotel Prescott, currently closed for renovation.  it has made a name for itself in SF.  the bar is still open as well as a small section of kitchen that makes brick oven pizzas and other small things.  the bar is actually decent place to hang at the counter, one of the bartenders is sort of on his way to flipping out.  expendy.','2009-11-30 16:29:57',2,64),(441,'re-opened!','2009-12-08 12:56:55',2,NULL),(442,'on first visit i think they\'ve done a good job here.  a bit of a way station for those waiting to get into Genoa next door; it also stands on its own nicely.  friendly, knowledgeable staff were correctly attentive and talkative.  \r\n\r\ni believe new owners took over genoa and also own this bar.  with a name that for soem reason i will never remember.  but it means &quot;next to&quot; so the ties with Genoa are purposeful.\r\n\r\nthe cocktail menu, at first glance, looks to be on the precious, sweet side, but upon closer inspection (drinking all 6 or 7 of them!) i can say that some thought was put into them like say the negroni with a cocktail glass rinsed in maraschino liqueur and the use of sweet AND dry vermouth.  tasty.  they even do the flaming orange trick.\r\n\r\ni only tasted the antipasti plate but if it is indicative of the menu things are looking good.  in a week word of mouth already has this place filled on a thursday at 6pm.  with all the (re)openings going on around town right now, and their capacity crowds you\'re likely to ask yourself: what recession?  i can\'t tell if it\'s me and the places i enjoy, but some of portland\'s punk is being replaced with a more urban professional feel, not just in the Pearl.  i hope the city can hold on to the best of both.','2009-12-11 14:27:56',2,65),(443,'Newly Reopened!  \nWhile visiting the bar next door we peeked into the newly remodeled dining room.  It\'s nicely appointed, with much more comfortable chairs.  it\'s still formal and gracious, but it\'s nice to have the windows.  maybe slightly less formal, more portland-friendly.  they\'ve moved from a 7 course to a 5 course fixed price, i believe about $55.  i am looking forward to checking it out again.  ','2009-12-09 13:24:18',2,65),(444,'just opened and can\'t wait to check it out.  if you\'ve never eaten across the street at his Pok Pok then you haven\'t had some of Portland\'s best food.  the huge bar makes it appear that they\'ll be hopping on the cocktail bandwagon.  i\'m excited that the lines may now be quelled slightly!','2009-12-09 20:02:12',2,NULL),(445,'cocktail craze spot','2009-12-30 14:42:56',2,NULL),(446,'place recommended','2009-12-30 14:44:04',2,NULL),(447,'This little place has been steadily gaining a following since it opened last year.  Does Portland need yet another neighborhood sushi spot?  In this case yes.  it\'s a cut above (pun intended) your normal neighborhood spot.  with interesting takes on common dishes and a better selection of rolls (for those that want them).  The sashimi is fresh.  The place was full when we dropped in on wednesday night.  the counter isn\'t as welcoming as some sushi bars, but the staff is friendly.  the decor needs to age a bit, but this place is definitely on our sushi go to list now.','2010-01-14 12:47:43',2,64),(448,'Pearl cocktail joint to check out.  ','2010-01-19 11:14:57',2,NULL),(449,'what\'s up with Branch?  is that a brand?','2010-01-19 11:16:23',2,NULL),(450,'This place is a treat.  Set up like a speak-easy, you knock on the door and an eye peaks out of the little opening that slides open.  &quot;we want to see the library.&quot;  you are taken through what looks like a surreal movie set, people watch you.  the hostess pushes a fake wall of books and you\'re in whiskey valjalla.  almost too hip, but pretty damn good.','2010-01-19 11:26:47',2,65),(520,'The new City Center development is pretty slick and this is one of the spectacles.  Three levels, all wrapped in beaded curtains, are very hip and sophisticated.  The servers are a bit tackily dressed, but this is probably expected in Vegas.  The service was good, the drinks made well.  A good spot to see and be seen at the beginning of the evening.  I don\'t think i would even bother later at night.','2011-01-20 23:18:12',2,65),(518,'record shop meets wine/beer bar.  open noon till 10.  like hall of records in SE Belmont.  want to check this out','2010-12-16 13:42:03',2,NULL),(519,'It was about 11 a.m. on a recent trek over to the alphabet district. A bit too early for lunch, and I was jonesing for a good breakfast. My usual go to spot, Besaw\'s, was a little too packed for a dine alone experience. Read: there was no room at the bar. Somehow I remembered a little haunt right around the corner, the Stepping Stone Cafe. Good news, there was a few spots at the bar. This is the kind of place that caters to regulars. Trouble is, they are the kind of folks spoofed in the upcoming series \'Portlandia\': Twenty somethings who have come here to retire. They all seem to know each other and all seem to have nothing to do but hang out well after finishing their meal. Shaggy bearded types inspired by the new crop of alternative bands. Okay so I\'m too old and too busy to hang here, but how is the food? Servicable at best. I had a Chicken Sausage scramble that could have used more creativity where seasoning is concerned. The Farmer Brothers coffee is perfect for the setting, but doesn\'t warrant a $1.75 price tag. Probably wouldn\'t go back, but glad they are still there, somehow making the revenue model work as the world around them goes high end condo.','2010-12-18 08:10:24',15,63),(517,'Yes, the burger is really good.\r\n\r\nWhen news that Gabriel Rucker was opening a bistro downtown the first thing people talked about was his amazing hamburger and how you would be able to get it now that there were more than 4 patties made in a day.  I\'m not sure I agree with using a hamburger as a baseline for judging top chefs, but that\'s neither here nor there.\r\n\r\nThis little strip of no man\'s land in the shadow of Big Pink has been seemingly the curse of potential restaurantiers, but maybe that era is over.  If a place called Hillbilly Bento can last as long as it has (though I\'m convinced it\'s a front since the food for shit) then Little Bird should be just fine.\r\n\r\nThey\'ve expanded the seating capacity by quite a bit.  There\'s a partial upstairs for extra dining.  The bar is a nice casual option.  For its first day of public service the staff was moving fairly smoothly.  We were greeted and treated quite well.  There are still a few kinks to work out (the coat hangers that force diners to sit under someone else\'s jacket all meal) but I\'m sure they will be soon.  \r\n\r\nI need to go back before I can rate the place, but you can bet I will.  With prices just above a normal neighborhood lunch it\'s a good option.  And an ambitious schedule of noon to midnight daily will serve the late-night cravings of a lot of happy folks.','2010-12-08 14:13:26',2,65),(515,'a must try, getting good reviews','2010-12-06 17:50:44',2,NULL),(516,'Kinda on the spendy side, but what\'s not these days.  We were hungry and the concierge recommended this spot.  On a saturday at 6pm the place was empty, but by the time we finished it was packed.  it\'s a slick, new, well-appointed but comfortable atmosphere with helpful staff and interesting items on the menu.  sorta a blast-from-the-past as the name might hint at.  the drinks were also well-done and not run of the mill.\r\n\r\na definite place to check out.','2010-12-06 17:57:51',2,65),(514,'This spot is classic.  i was craving noodles (soup actually) the other night and my buddy remembered reading a review of a noodle spot on broadway.  off we went.  at this point i was pretty loaded on db cocktails, so my review is more experiential than detail/fact-based; a return visit is necessary and desired.\r\n\r\nwe ordered the dumplings and they were fucking good.  like ginger dumplings at dim sum, they were mad tastyl but not overpowering.  a bit chewy, but i think that was good.\r\n\r\nwe shared a couple noodle plates, 1 with the squid and the other with -- fuck if i know/care.  they were both great.  the noodles really are wonderful.  wide, chewy, tasty.\r\n\r\ni remember being a bit paranoid the whole time.  i think we were making a bit of noise and it seemed like maybe it was Frank himself working the floor.  when my buddy ordered a beer, i kept trying to butt in, embarrassed by his not-so-subtle racist outbursts.  i thought he kept saying &quot;hi!&quot; and nodding in a derogatory way but it just turned out that he was ordering Hite beer.  my bad.\r\n\r\nwhat really stood out to my drunk mind, though, was the unassuming location.  it\'s on the part of broadway where the houses are converted into storefronts.  this may seem quaint to some people, to me it just feels ghetto.  but whateverquest.  we had to wait a couple minutes, and it seemed like there was always a table or two of folks waiting.  the furniture is cheap as fuck, the feet are covered with -- i shit you not -- cut up tennis balls.  it\'s that no-frills, pocket all profits, make tasty food ethos and it\'s just fine.\r\n\r\ngo.','2010-11-15 12:45:47',2,65),(512,'Great SE standby. Well worth keeping in the rotation of places. A typical meal for two with apps and a bottle wine will run about $80. Not bad considering the great tastes this little place produces. High quality food, but laid back atmosphere.  Jeans and a t-shirt fit equally well as a suit. ','2010-10-21 12:51:03',5,65),(513,'I was actually craving Indian buffet when i went to lunch today, but instead i was in for a welcome surprise.  The Indian joint was gone but in its place was a new Hamburger Mary\'s.  I had just been talking to someone a few days before about HM\'s.  We had one in SF when i was living there and it was this great mix of straight meets gay in a hilarious way.  A proud queer staff serves haggy straight women and just about every other group you can imagine.  The standout is great service and great hamburgers.  it\'s a laid back atmosphere with outrageous staff.\r\n\r\ni really hope this place can find its niche.  it\'s on the north bus mall right off burnside, so it\'s in the right neighborhood; but it\'s one of those weird blocks that just looks lifeless.  welcome Hamburger Mary\'s!','2010-11-11 14:12:45',2,64),(486,'this was so long ago i forget the meal; but that\'s no indication of its quality.  i just have a bad memory.  i do remember this place being architecturally unique and an all around great place to dine.  superb service.  this is a must if you\'re in calgary.','2010-05-28 11:38:54',2,65),(487,'The restaurant here is a great stop.  Top notch service and food.  They specialize in game from the area.  but it\'s not some dank old log cabin funk, it\'s the real deal.  I had a mushroom soup that was one of the best things i\'ve ever tasted.  it\'s been too long to remember, but this is a great stop','2010-05-28 11:42:20',2,65),(488,'One of my favorite meals ever.  We stumbled into this place -- on an island in a park -- during the lunch hour and it was like entering a different dimension.  The pace slowed, people were all smiles, there was a raging fire in a huge fireplace, it was sparsely filled, but those there winking as if to say: &quot;ah, you\'ve found it.  welcome.&quot;\r\n\r\nservice: impeccable.  we sat at the counter and had a server bring whatever was recommended.  a warm beet salad with goat cheese, this may be where the trend all started!  everything she brought was great.  and conversation was lively.  she had us tasting wines just for fun.  \r\n\r\nmagic','2010-05-28 11:48:27',2,65),(489,'Great food and atmosphere.  Spendy.  If you want a nice night out in Whistler, this could be the place.  Good for a romantic meal.  Great service','2010-05-28 11:51:11',2,64),(490,'Great restaurant right on the walk.  We had great service.  Decent wine list, helpful, attentive staff.  Highly recommended.  Tip: if there\'s a wait, sneak up to the up upstairs bar!','2010-05-28 12:05:23',2,64),(491,'Komboucha','2010-06-01 16:49:44',2,NULL),(492,'Somehow this place was exactly as i had imagined it.  which was a good thing indeed.  the atmosphere is warm and welcoming.  the service is professional and attentive.  the night we went the menu was slightly Southern in bent and they did a good job on the dishes.  plenty of tasty starters and entreees to choose from.  there are some interesting specialty cocktails listed and the bartenders mix with care and skill.\r\n\r\nthe bar was the perfect place for a casual dinner with small group of us.  there were plenty of single professionals having a post-work dinner/drink.  this could be a Go To if i worked in the area.  \r\n\r\nthe prices are fairly steep but that might just be my Portland side talking.  drinks ~ $12; starters ~ $14; entrees ~ $28;\r\n\r\n','2010-06-08 14:38:40',2,64),(493,'As we were finishing up the table next to us all got bowls of wonton noodles soup that looked fucking GOOD!  reminded me of that little spot in Portland, but this would have used quality ingredients.  \r\n\r\nwe had sesame chicken; dry braised green beans; hot/sour soup and rice.  This was a perfect sharing meal for the two of us and was damn tasty.  \r\n\r\nin case you\'re out of the loop, this place is brought to you by the folks that brought you House of Nanking.  some of the popular dishes appear here.  and the patriarch still dismisses your order and suggests other things.  feel free to go with his suggestions or to over-ride them.\r\n\r\nbesides the bill not showing up, the service was decent and food came out hot and good.  a very reasonable price for the meal also.  another spot i would frequent if i still worked at CNET.','2010-06-08 14:46:17',2,65),(494,'One of the newest restaurants to open up on NE 28th actually fits in nicely without overlapping the already established spots in the neighborhood.  City State is a diner replete with booths and table seating.  it\'s a shame there isn\'t more counter space, not to mention the PPA (Portland Passive Aggressive) douchebag sitting in the middle chair of the 3 seat side.  \r\n\r\nOpen a little over a month they seem to have worked out most kinks.  We came in around 2:30 on a saturday, just after a rush and the servers were still a bit harried.  After settling in and getting coffee and wasabi bloody mary (interesting, but will probably try one of there other takes on the classic breakfast drink).  The hollandaise sauce on the biscuit-bottomed benedict was tasty.  J got a croque madame and couldn\'t stop talking about the cholesterol attack she might have.  needless to say, portions here are not an issue.  yet, it\'s not quite Black Bear obese portions which is nice.\r\n\r\nThe vibe was good at 2:30 but i would worry about it being a bit hectic during a rush.  there\'s a slight atmosphere of protectiveness amongst the diners.  will definitely be going back. ','2010-07-18 15:40:59',2,64),(495,'A nice addition to the thriving little neighborhood at 50th and Division.  The attraction of this new place has to be the huge outdoor area that feels like a western saloon outside of a big city.  lots of tables and dirt and even silly &quot;cornhole&quot; beanbag throwing game.\r\n\r\nservice was great.  decent selection of beers on tap and some good cocktails.','2010-07-18 16:41:25',2,64),(497,'Pedestrian course, but actually kind of fun.  Laid back, not too crowded, real baskets.  you sort of circle the landscaping around some church parking lot.  on the back side there are some nice spots to chill, smoke some weed, shotgun some beers and then start again.  location is fairly easy to get to from Portland if you don\'t want to go all the way out to Pier Park.  12 holes.','2010-07-18 17:01:36',2,64),(498,'This place is L E G I T legit!  I\'m still sort of amazed that the Senator even knew about this place; well, not really, people seemed to be flocking here from miles around just to order a stack of home-made tortillas to go.\r\n\r\nThis place is sorta on the other side of the train tracks/airplane runways, but it\'s not too sketch.  it\'s just one of those rundown hovel style buildings that Phoenix has the market on.  two big rooms, a window to order and a bunch of tables.  \r\n\r\nAZ-style mexican food, not cali/mission.  but the melted cheese on everything is fucking good.  they seemed to have no problem with us bringing in our own beer cause they weren\'t selling it.\r\n\r\nnext time you\'re flying in/out of sky harbor add a little extra time and hit this spot.','2010-07-20 12:41:52',2,65),(499,'it is indeed a pretty big-ass sandwich.  the roll is tasty and the meat (i tried roast turkey) was tasty.  however, the MASSIVE load of fries cooked into the beast was a bit much.  the fries were greasy and included way too many.  and then not enough of the super tasty meat.  next time i\'ll ask for frie-less and extra meat.  nice extras to add, like horse radish and rooster sauce, but they charge a pretty penny for each extra so that sangoo can add up.  nice folk working there.  sandwich takes a bit to be made so be patient.  ','2010-07-21 16:04:35',2,64),(500,'daily brunch 9 - 3','2010-07-26 15:01:33',2,NULL),(501,'Gr&uuml;ner is &quot;Cozy Alpine Cuisine&quot; according the their website.  Ok.  i\'ll buy that.\r\n\r\nthe experience was definitely cozy, especially on a cold, crisp winter afternoon.  the staff was helpful and smart and cute and hip.  i haven\'t had enough of the food to base my review solely on that, but i will be returning.  the burger lived up to its reputation, according to my dining companion.  he ate it meticulously slow as if remembering times of hard-to-find food (he\'s a bit older).  my chicken sandwich was not as good as i would have hoped but it hit the spot.  at this price point you knew who was going to be in attendance, and they were there in droves, even at the lunch hour.  it was nice to see quite a bit of quaffing given that it was lunch.  Portland\'s eatery for that strata that doesn\'t need to work on any given friday.\r\n\r\nthe atmosphere was warm.  the manager was fawning over the table over and i felt like i could join that club if i worked on it.  by 12:30 the place was over-run, but the service never slacked and i plan to put it in rotation.','2010-12-03 14:19:45',2,65),(502,'AMAZING FOOD!  I would trade an average orgasm for a meal from Kin. As well, Flip is the bartender, which for my money, is the best mixologist in Portland. Just remember, his secret ingredient is booze.','2010-09-30 13:00:53',5,66),(503,'I give this place a C-.  My Sturjin was overcooked -- and you can\'t overcook a sturjyn!  The waitress had a crush on me but my wife would tell me all about it later.','2010-10-07 14:36:05',16,63),(504,'This place is being slept on.  That\'s bad for business but good for those looking for a great place to eat without a wait.  Roost makes tasty food.  The dishes might seem precious at first glance, but that would belittle the incredible tastes they get into each elegant dish.  It\'s not just the average Northwest fare.  They\'re putting out unusual -- and some classic -- dishes.  The menu is refreshingly short, no filler, just great food.\r\n\r\nThere may have been some hiccups on their soft launch -- how else to explain the non-existent lift from the excitement of the passers-by before the doors opened.  If there were, the hiccups are gone now.  Great, friendly service abounds.\r\n\r\nThe big surprise is the weekend brunch.  Unusually savory dishes abound.  Of course they have eggs -- they call brunch &quot;eggs till 2pm&quot; but these are not your average egg dishes.  These are strange new creations that i\'m still thinking about a month later.  Might be the best brunch i\'ve had this year.\r\n\r\nGive this place a shot at keeping their doors open.  You and they deserve it!','2010-12-08 23:38:02',2,65),(505,'I agree with the other bozo: this place isn\'t making the cut yet.  We just wanted a drink, we were outnumbered 10 to 1 by staff and still had to tackle a server just to take our order.  Then it took ten fucking minutes to make our drink!  The cocktail menu is your basic \'cocktail craze\' menu with nothing added to personalize.  Don\'t come here for the drinks i guess is what i\'m saying.\n\nif the opportunity arises i may try the food some time, but i\'m not going out of my way.','2010-10-11 19:43:03',2,63),(485,'Don\'t let the cheesiness of the name and location scare you away.  This is Banff, the whole fucking town is cheeseball.  And here you can escape for a little bit and have a great meal.  I forget the chef\'s name, but she\'s relatively famous in some circle.  Anyway, she was there and nice as all hell.  Food was fresh and interesting takes on Southwestern fare.  It\'s always interesting to see &quot;foreign&quot; takes on American cuisine.  Success here.  ','2010-05-28 11:30:31',2,65),(484,'It\'s a wonder i haven\'t been here before now. This place is wonderful. In an unassuming industrial location, part of the newly renovated Olympic Mills building, Olympic Provisions is \"Oregon\'s first USDA certified meat-curing facility.\" it\'s like a european counter/deli style restaurant. the wait staff is great and the food preps are helpful and in good moods. the food is spectacular and a great beer selection. it\'s a must.','2010-04-21 14:18:07',2,65),(479,'heard good things','2010-03-14 21:43:48',2,NULL),(480,'It\'s a wonder i haven\'t been here before now.  This place is wonderful.  In an unassuming industrial location, part of the newly renovated Olympic Mills building, Olympic Provisions is &quot;Oregon\'s first USDA certified meat-curing facility.&quot;  it\'s like a european counter/deli style restaurant.  the wait staff is great and the food preps are helpful and in good moods.  the food is spectacular and a great beer selection.  it\'s a must','2010-04-21 15:13:16',2,65),(477,'Decent greasy spoon breakfast in the keys.  the deep fried hash browns rule.','2010-03-01 15:01:17',2,64),(478,'This trendy, loud restaurant on hip Las Olas gets crowded, so be prepared to wait for a table.  The night we went there was a great swing band playing that we had to yell over to have a conversation.  Martinis were mixed well.  the decor was chain-feeling, but nice chain feeling and warm and comfortable.  service was excellent.  i\'ve noticed at higher end restaurants in miami area that sparkling water is sort of implicit with meals, though of course paid for.\r\n\r\nthe food here was above average but nothing outrageous.  indeed, it was as good as one might expect.  i would actually recommend this place.','2010-03-01 15:06:56',2,64),(476,'Cheesy but who cares.  This open air tiki bar is right on the water with sand floors and thatched roofs.  The bartenders are not very good, but that\'s not a problem early in the day where there\'s no one there.  it\'s a nice place to waste a few hours and get some really sweet tropical drinks.','2010-03-01 14:55:08',2,64),(475,'Very cheesy, but still a good spot to check out if you\'ve got spare time and are hungry.  another resorty feeling spot, you can watch an awesome sunset like we did from the island dock.  The service was friendly, but they lost their attention and one in our party felt the brunt of a complicated order going bad.  on the spendy side for its caliber, this is just another place &quot;to do.&quot;  there\'s the requisite burning man fire spinner and beat-machine-fueled guitarist/singer going through island-proper covers.\r\n\r\n','2010-03-01 14:36:21',2,64),(473,'This nice little spot right on the beach was surprisingly decent.  Divided between a bar and a sit-down, hosted restaurant area, the location is hard to beat.  The food quality varied but the menu had much to choose from.  Service fine, drinks good, worked out well.  This is a place that caters to the older crowd of the Keys, but don\'t let that scare you away.  When the manager comes over to make small talk just smile and let her move along.  \r\n\r\nRecommended','2010-03-01 14:22:11',2,64),(474,'With a name like this, what\'s not to love?  You get what you expect from a place like this.  Right on the water, the vibe is island and it\'s almost resort-y in its overall build-out.  there\'s a stage for bands to play, salty bartender, locals, tourists, the whole nine.  The jerk chicken wings were great.  the fish sandwiches were not bad.  the drinks: who knows?  my hangover was legendary enough to opt for an iced tea.\r\n\r\nThe owner\'s son has a winery in Lodi, CA, where he makes what could only be a shit-tasting wine called Big Pecker.  i\'m sure they sell way more Big Pecker merchandise than wine itself.  \r\n\r\nIt\'s not the best, but i\'d still say go if you\'ve got nothing better to do.','2010-03-01 14:29:39',2,64),(471,'i think this is one of the higher rated breakfast spots in Key West.  it can be hard to dig past the marketing hype and find the local favorites, but this one seems to suit both.\r\n\r\nService was slow at first but then came around.  The bloody marys were tasty, the coffee good, the food great.  atmosphere was a little, well, tacky, just like the rest of FLA.  but if you\'re a breakfast person and find yourself in Key West, this place should do you proper.','2010-03-01 14:11:48',2,64),(472,'This place seems to be about equally filled with tourists and locals alike.  The place is legit.  Fish sandwiches served in a patchwork shack built up around a food cart.  The vibe is good, the beer is cold, the food is palateable.  Great for people watching and being watched by the locals.  Feel free to find a piece of chalk and write on something.  And look for the Chuco card.\r\n\r\nRecommended.','2010-03-01 14:17:33',2,65),(470,'The Texas style chicken egg roll thingies are the highlight.  The rest of it goes downhill fast.  It was late, raining and cold and we needed food badly.  This place had a table and we took it.  Our server was attentive because he was bored and just watching the olympics on the big screen blaring by us.  \r\n\r\nIt was our first round of island drinks and island style, but we knew we had only up to go.  You realize quickly that the Keys are usually warm and thus the outdoor-ness of every place.  If only we had had weather to match.  instead the women ran off to buy cheap sweaters to keep us warm.  which meant i wore a woman\'s zipper hoodie with &quot;Key West&quot; in large letters on the front for the rest of the trip.\r\n\r\nI think most of us rushed to the bathroom after this meal, but the drinks during kept the mood high.  Look for the Chuco card on the palm tree on your way in.\r\n\r\nanother place to avoid.','2010-03-01 14:07:39',2,63),(469,'At first i thought it was the douchebag from the parking lot who shouted, &quot;who wants to try my nuts!&quot;  I only had to turn around to see the bartender repeat the phrase, this time louder.  I applied for the grant.  Thus the coconut monkey filled with pina colada.  This was our first stop on our FLA Keys escapades.  Right on one of the waterways in Key Largo, this place hasn\'t been touched up since the seventies.  The service was spotty, but a good way to slip into &quot;Key time&quot; to get the trip off to a start.\r\n\r\nYou should probably skip this place.\r\n\r\nAfter our trip to the Keys i realized just how ironic the phrase &quot;Attitude Free Zone&quot; is.','2010-03-01 14:02:22',2,63),(468,'This high end pan asian restaurant tries to control every aspect of your experience.  There\'s a little spot light built into the table\'s center where your &quot;curator&quot; places a menu to tell you how he is going to order for you.  \r\n\r\nThe food is great, albeit precious.  The take on seaweed salad: outstanding.  There was somewhat of a rushed feeling as the place tries to handle over 300 reservations an evening.  Food is shared, though it is not served for you which would have been desireable with a larger party than the 3 or us.\r\n\r\nThe service was sometimes curt.  They were trying very hard to come off as authoritative, sometimes being rude in the process.  New Yorkers and South Beachers seem to know how to handle this well, my west coast passiveness had no chance.  Either was a great meal here is guaranteed.  It\'ll cost you, though.','2010-03-01 13:56:39',2,65),(466,'This spot on Stone Street is crowded by the post-work financial crowd and then mellower later in the evening.  Pretty run of the mill, but fine for the limited options when you\'re at the low end of manhattan.  \r\n\r\nsomewhat jocular/meat market feeling, with lots of that finanical attitude.  ','2010-03-01 13:20:46',2,64),(467,'Nice little bar with lots of rotating beers on tap.  Also an emphasis on good liquors with chalkboards telling you what\'s available at what price.  There\'s also a patio and an outdoor spot for smokers, albeit sort of a dirty afterthought.\r\n\r\nGood place to sample lots of high-octane beer and roll right into the liquor assuring a drunken afternoon.','2010-03-01 13:26:04',2,64),(465,'this place is a trip.  it\'s sort of a higher end chinese spot.  has its own cookbook.  there are little stations here and there where people help to serve because, of course, chinese food is meant to be family style.  this is a good idea.  but they are so severe, and there is some hierarchy between them.  i got scolded for asking questions and had to bite my tongue.  one of those very new york situations that someone less sophisticated might not handle well.\r\n\r\nthe food was not bad, but i still haven\'t settled my urge for great chinese food since moving from San Francisco.','2010-03-01 13:14:11',2,64),(464,'Another good go-to for a decent brunch/deli meal in NYC.  since i\'m not from there i can tell there would be camps of new yorkers who might shun a spot like this, but coming from the land w/o deli, this place will do just fine.  great atmostphere, very genuine.  tile and booths, the whole nine.  plus, great service.  food took a while to come but it was crowded/weekend when we went so very understandable.  don\'t expect cocktails for brunch.  they have vodka and can make a pretty bad bloody and, well, a drinkable screwdriver.  i think they have champagne and can do mimosas.\r\n\r\nthe food itself was good.  i would definitely return.','2010-03-01 13:04:52',2,64),(463,'I really liked this dinner spot in the theatre district.  it\'s Italian with a bunch of deli-like side dishes to choose from.  great service, nice atmosphere and decor, good food.  it felt very convivial and engaging.  we got a bunch of salad and pasta side dishes and a nice piece of fish.  our table was covered with plates and glasses and we happily shared all.\r\n','2010-03-01 12:59:15',2,65),(462,'This was a nice little spot.  Not the friendliest staff, in fact I almost had to address the hostess when she rudely told me to move my seat so she could keep squeezing by me in this crowded restaurant.  i realize that new york is crowded and most restaurants are claustrophobic, but there was something in the way she said it, or my hangover, that almost got her a dressing down.\r\n\r\non the food side, things were better.  a little bit precious, the small portions were delicately prepared and dished and retakes on the familiar.  the pork-belly benedict had two unnaturally shaped squares of pork belly that was deeply striated with fat.  most people would have found it lovely, it was on the fatty side for me personally.  but really the food was quite nice all around on the limited menu.\r\n\r\nnot the best bloody mary.  i guess i would recommend giving the place a shot, but i think it wouldn\'t fall into heavy rotation in a city with such diverse offerings.','2010-03-01 12:53:13',2,64),(461,'One of the things I love most about this place is that it\'s cash only unless you have a Peter Luger credit card?  it just works so well with the fact that everyone that talks about this place says how it\'s such a mob spot.  this place is a classic for sure.  even though the patronage is getting younger, the place still feels like it hasn\'t changed in forever.  \r\n\r\nthe steak was great, the appetizers classic and good.  the service fast and curt.  it\'s a must experience.  you might have to call way in advance to get a reservation, but there\'s a bar to wait at (crowded on weekends).','2010-03-01 12:35:51',2,65),(460,'As one might expect, the cocktails here are not cheap.  But anyone who appreciates high-end hotel bars knows, drinks are usually made well, are not skimpy, and service is impeccable.  The Ritz bar mostly lives up to the expectations.  Not a lot of character, but quick service, good drinks, assortment of nuts.  I went with a group of 4 distinguished looking folks and the service was much better than when I went alone at closing time, but I would say this is a hotel bar experience sans any hipness (probably due to its BFE Battery Park location).','2010-03-01 11:49:42',2,65),(459,'During a recent visit to California, we were looking for a good cocktail. When we went into a place that looked promising- but that had only beer and wine - the server told us to go to Copa d\' Oro. I\'ll have to thank her next time I see her. Copa has a $5 happy hour and a solid list of cocktails that qualify. As such, it was packed on an early Friday evening. So we bellied up to the bar. The mixologist was extremely knowledgable and made us a couple of excellent drinks. For me: a variation on an old fashioned, and for my wife: a mojito. Happy hour cocktails aren\'t usually this good. Sure- you can\'t call Maker\'s for the $5, but the drinks were made with a TLC that exceeded expectations. With fresh juice and top notch ingredients. The clientele trends younger, but nobody seemed to mind that we were there. You may want to get there early to get a comfortable spot. Still, if you aspire to make good drinks at home, then this is a good place to sit at the bar and learn. If we didn\'t have a dinner reservation to get to, I would have been there longer. A must do if in Santa Monica. ','2010-02-10 13:30:03',15,66),(456,'High praise, must try this place','2010-02-08 15:04:26',2,NULL),(457,'Coming from San Francisco I have a hard time finding Chinese food in Portland that i like.  FuJin just down the block from this spot is decent, but the space is not a draw.  Lucky Strike serves up authentic Sichuan food (read: HOT).  The service was smiling.  i just hope they are able to break the curse of this high-overturn space.  good drinks.  there are still a few bumps from its recent opening, but once ironed out it should be fine.  the dishes were so spicy we were crying with joy.  hurt so good.','2010-07-18 16:51:11',2,65),(458,'Every town has one of those restaurants that has a great remote location that you pass on your way someplace else and think: &quot;one of these days I gotta try that place.&quot; And so it was that we ended up at Gladstone\'s, the iconic seafood restaurant that you can\'t miss when driving Highway 1 between Malibu and Santa Monica. Let me start by saying the food is not good and it is way overpriced. Nevertheless, the location, IF and ONLY IF you are seated at a window table overlooking the ocean, makes it worthwhile experience - at least once. We went on a very stormy night in LA with a friend of my wife\'s that she had not seen in 15 years and his girlfriend. I had never met either of them. Huge flood lights which illuminated the pounding surf and driving rain provided an enchanting -even mesmerizing - setting in which to have a conversation. Two hours later, it felt like they were old friends. Back to the food: we were told that the Mojito was voted \'the best in LA\' so we started with a round of same. Never believe a claim like this. It was too sweet, and at $13. . .I wish it had lived up to the server\'s hype. For appetizers we had calamari and a shrimp cocktail, large portions but unimpressive. For dinner:  We split the tuna and chased it with some clam chowder . The tuna was tough, and the chowder flavorless and monochromatic like eating a bowl of cream. Our friends were less than impressed with their meals as well. You could probably have the same experience with just the appetizers and a few drinks, then move on. When I told the locals about my experience they said \'go to the Reel In up the street instead.\' Advice I will heed next time.','2010-02-11 07:39:55',15,64),(455,'The second German-themed bar (the other: Spints) to open recently in Portland.  This place is immaculately remodeled and is welcoming.  Finally a bar with the glass washers in the beer-spill tray!  Food was good, mostly sausage.  Great selection of beers and the proper mugs to drink them from.  They even have boots to drink from when you have a worthy group of friends.  The kicker here is that it opens onto a courtyard of food carts.  This would be cool if it wasn\'t so damn depressing in the rain and when most of them are closed or suck.  The food cart thing burned so bright.  The summer will rock there, though.  This lot is not well curated, but the breakfast cart is the fucking goods!  And the market will adjust the food come summer and it will be a destination.  ','2010-01-29 15:39:40',2,64),(453,'Great little neighborhood bar. The owner is from Alaska and has created a friendly place for all.  Right on the number 4 and 14 bus lines. ','2010-01-28 15:03:14',5,65),(454,'Not one, but two people thought now was the time to open a german-themed bar in Portland (the other: Prost).  Not that they\'re going to pop up like whiskey bars are doing now in this country, but they\'re on to something.  This place is newly renovated in a thoughtful manner.  Lots of dark woods and colors gives the place warmth and comfort.  There is a communal table by the front taken from tradition of sending the drunk people to a table of their own.  Of course beer is a priority and the selection nice.  The name of the bar is German for &quot;locker.&quot;  and they have little lockers where locals can store their steins between visits.  We tried a few apps, like cheese board and others, all which were good.  I plan on returning to try a true German meal.  Recommended!','2010-01-29 15:36:48',2,64),(451,'This new(ish) breakfast spot opened without fanfare, duh.  who *doesn\'t* soft launch these days?  if you were to take out an ad you might fail, afterall.  if it\'s not cool on Twitter then don\'t even open!  But some places live up to the hype.  And, really, this place doesn\'t have any hipper-than-thou attitude tossed in when people discuss it.  They just sound like excited childre, cause, well, you get to make your own pancakes at the table!  \r\nAnd all gimmicks aside, the place works well.  The food selection was just about the right assortment of egg dishes on top of the pancakes.  Tasty.  service was attentive and friendly.  cocktail menu was thoughtful, all local spirits.  whoever put this place together knows what they\'re doing.  even a large waiting area because you know you\'re waiting.  it\'s breakfast after all.  how are you not going to have to wait?  it\'s interesting to see how Pine State drew the line from Cricket and now this place is drawing the line from Pine State.   maybe it\'ll spread down and over the hill to Montavilla.  i guess it already sort of has....','2010-01-20 17:07:24',2,65),(521,'One of the bars in this well-appointed section of the City Center development.  This bar, with its white starkness and classic design has a good vibe.  The service and drinks were not quite as good here, but it\'s a comfortable place to sit and people watch.  A good stop if you\'re with a friend and want to chat.  I wouldn\'t mind having this be my hotel bar at all.','2011-01-20 23:20:45',2,65),(522,'This place made me enjoy Vegas again.  Vegas kind of grew up a bit over the many years since i\'d visited.  Now there are great restaurants and hotels that aren\'t too disneyfied and plastic.  The Aria is gorgeous, with incredible details everywhere and not cheap ones.  There are a ton of bars sprinkled around the main floor.  The rooms are completely remote-controlled with awesome beds and bathrooms.  Highly recommended.  I would definitely look to stay in the City Center development next time i\'m in vegas.','2011-01-20 23:24:41',2,66),(523,'Eaten here often, Lunch and Dinner (they do breakfast). Always very good food. Unique menu items, interesting combinations of ingrediants that are succesful.','2011-01-28 00:52:37',14,65),(524,'customers stink of hipness and beer snobbery.  reminded me that beer snobs are fucking weirdos.  hope the place shapes up.','2011-01-28 00:54:58',2,63),(2000,'here\'s a review\n','2011-01-29 01:29:29',0,65),(2001,'this should add a second review.  ','2011-01-29 02:20:39',0,63),(2002,'testing the add functionality, wasn\'t working at hobnob','2011-01-29 16:04:04',0,64),(2003,'Review 7','2011-01-29 16:58:28',0,61),(2004,'This place fucking rules! ','2011-01-29 17:07:12',0,66),(2005,'It tastes about the same as out looks. Friendly enough, your basic booth and counter joint. The chili was decent, possibly canned. \n\nHas your classic coffee mugs waiting on the table. I\'ll post back in a while if anything goes wrong.','2011-02-01 19:57:19',0,63),(2006,'The Twilight Zone of sushi restaurants.  Zombie-like wait staff hover around during the lunch hour, only stopping if you make eye contact.  Slow pace; don\'t come if you\'re pressed for time or have only an hour for lunch. \n\nGood udon bowls, fair sushi, warm drinking.  water. ','2011-02-03 13:04:13',0,62),(2036,'A Portland institution where old and young come for a decent prime rib style meal or to hang out in the lounge and dance to good R\'n\'B.\r\n\r\nPlush booths, carpet, wrought iron and the metal blimp rolling around to serve fresh beef at your table. It\'s a blast from the past that won\'t break the bank. Try out, it just might go into regular rotation. \r\n\r\nJust make sure to wear the right shoes to dinner so you can cut a rug after they cut you a hunk of beef. You\'ll need the exercise! ','2011-02-12 23:06:42',2,65),(2021,'second review\r\n','2011-02-11 23:53:04',2,66),(2009,'body of review!','2011-02-11 02:27:01',0,66),(2010,'body of review!','2011-02-11 02:27:41',0,66),(2011,'body of review!','2011-02-11 02:27:49',0,66),(2012,'another freakin review!','2011-02-11 02:28:32',0,64),(2013,'Not getting prices yet! \r\n','2011-02-11 02:53:03',0,65),(2014,'This is my test location!','2011-02-11 13:40:05',0,63),(2015,'my new rating should affect average','2011-02-11 20:12:51',0,63),(2016,'is price and rating going through?','2011-02-11 20:51:17',0,62),(2017,'another priceline try','2011-02-11 21:11:17',0,62),(2029,'very second review!','2011-02-12 00:49:27',2,62),(2019,'this review by skip!','2011-02-11 23:36:21',2,62),(2023,'second review','2011-02-12 00:01:39',2,66),(2024,'initial','2011-02-12 00:36:51',2,62),(2028,'initialize!','2011